<section xml:id="mod-forms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Review of Modular Forms</title>
  <p>
    In this section we are going to review some basic facts about modular forms.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-upper-half-plane">
    <title>The upper half-plane</title>
    <p>
      By <m>SL_2</m> we will mean the group of <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices with determinant <m>1</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>\gamma = \begin{pmatrix}
                        a \amp b \\
                        c \amp d
                    \end{pmatrix} \in \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{R}), z \in \mathbb{C} \setminus \{-\frac{d}{c}\}</m>, and let <m>\gamma.z = \frac{az + b}{cz + d}</m>, then
                    <me>
                      \text{Im}(\gamma.z) = \frac{ad - bc}{\lvert cz + d \rvert^2}\text{Im}(z) = \frac{\text{Im}(z)}{\lvert cz + d \rvert^2}

                    </me>
      We denote <m>\mathfrak{h} = \{z \mid \text{Im}(z) > 0\}</m> to be the upper half plane. It is stable under <m>z \mapsto \gamma.z</m> and we clearly have <m>(\gamma_1\gamma_2).z = \gamma_1.(\gamma_2.z)</m>.

    </p>
    <proposition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The transformation action <m>z \mapsto \gamma.z</m> defines a group action of <m>\text{SL}_2(\mathbb{R})</m> on <m>\mathfrak{h}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The proof is routine verification. 
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                We have <m>\begin{pmatrix}
                  1 \amp 0 \\
                  0 \amp 1
                  \end{pmatrix} . z = \frac{1 \cdot z + 0}{0 \cdot z + 1} = z
                </m>
                Hence the first property is verified.


              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Follows from the fact before the proposition by routine veritification.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
    <proposition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{dx \wedge dy}{y^2}</m> is invariant under <m>\text{SL}_2(\mathbb{R})</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We have the required action as <m>\gamma.z = \frac{az + b}{cz + d}</m>, and so if we let <m>z = x + iy</m> and <m>z' = x' + iy'</m> the required transformation we have
          <me>
            y' = \frac{y}{(cx + d)^2 + c^2y^2}
          </me>
          Computing the Jacobian of the transformation we get that
          <me>
            J = \frac{1}{((cx + d)^2 + c^2y^2)^2}
          </me>
          Now the wedge product of the transform is 
          <me>
            dx' \wedge dy' = J \cdot dx \wedge dy = \frac{1}{((cx + d)^2 + c^2y^2)^2} \cdot dx \wedge dy
          </me>
          Now using the expression for <m>y'</m> we have 
          <me>
            \frac{dx' \wedge dy'}{(y')^2} = \frac{\frac{1}{((cx + d)^2 + c^2y^2)^2} \cdot dx \wedge dy}{\frac{y}{(cx + d)^2 + c^2y^2}^2} = \frac{dx \wedge dy}{y^2}
          </me>
          And hence the result follows.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </proposition>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f: \mathfrak{h} \to \mathbb{C}</m> be a meromorphic function and <m>\gamma = \begin{pmatrix}
            a \amp b \\
            c \amp d
          \end{pmatrix} \in \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{R})</m>. If <m>k \in \mathbb{Z}</m>, we define the weight <m>k</m> action of <m>\text{SL}_2(\mathbb{R})</m> by
          <me>
            (f \mid_k \gamma)(z) = (cz + d)^{-k} f(\gamma.z)
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proposition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We have
          <me>
            (f \mid_k \gamma_1)\mid_k \gamma_2 = f \mid_k \gamma_1\gamma_2
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          We prove the following claim first
          <claim>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let <m>\gamma \in \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{R})</m> and <m>z \in \mathfrak{h}</m> and let <m>j(\gamma,z) = cz + d</m>. Then we have
                <me>
                  j(\gamma_1\gamma_2,z) = j(\gamma_1,\gamma_2 z)j(\gamma_2,z)
                </me>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <proof>
              <p>
                Let <m>\gamma_1 = \begin{pmatrix}
                  a_1 \amp b_1 \\
                  c_1 \amp d_1
                  \end{pmatrix}
                </m>
                and <m>\gamma_2 = \begin{pmatrix}
                  a_2 \amp b_2 \\
                  c_2 \amp d_2
                \end{pmatrix}
                </m>
                then we have <m>j(\gamma_1\gamma_2,z) = (c_1a_2 + d_1c_2)z + (c_1b_2 + d_1d_2)</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                On the other hand we have <m>j(\gamma_1,\gamma_2z) = c_1(\frac{a_2z + b_2}{c_2z + d_2}) + d_1 = \frac{j(\gamma_1\gamma_2,z)}{j(\gamma_2,z)}</m>
                </p>
            </proof>
          </claim>
          We observe that 
          <me>
            (f \mid_k \gamma)(z) = j(\gamma,z)^{-k} f(\gamma.z)
          </me>
          Now using the claim and routine verification
          <m>
          \begin{align*}
          (f \mid_k \gamma_1)\mid_k \gamma_2 \amp= j(\gamma_2,z)^{-k}(f \mid_k \gamma_1)(\gamma_2 z) \\
          \amp= j(\gamma_2,z)^{-k}(j(\gamma_1,\gamma_2 z)^{-k} f(\gamma_1 \gamma_2 z)) \\
          \amp=  f \mid_k \gamma_1 \gamma_2
          \end{align*}
          </m>
      </p>  
      </proof>
    </proposition>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-def-mod-forms">
    <title>Definition of modular forms</title>
    <p>
      We define modular forms as follows.
    </p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\Gamma</m> be a subgroup of <m>\mathbb{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z})</m> of finite index, <m>\chi</m> is a finite order character of <m>\Gamma</m>(i.e <m>\chi(\Gamma) \in \mu_N</m>). <m>f: \mathfrak{h} \to \mathbb{C}</m> is modular form of weight <m>k</m>, character <m>\chi</m> for <m>\Gamma</m>, if:
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f</m> is holomorphic on <m>\mathfrak{h}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f \mid_k \gamma = \chi(\gamma)f</m>, if <m>\gamma \in \Gamma</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>f</m> is slowly increasing at infinity i.e <m>\forall \gamma \in \Gamma \setminus \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z}), \: \exists C(\gamma),r(\gamma) \ni \lvert f \mid_k \gamma(z) \rvert \leq y^{r(\gamma)}</m>, if <m>y \geq C(\gamma)</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>       
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\Gamma</m> is a congruence subgroup if <m>\Gamma \supset \Gamma(N) = \text{Ker}(\text{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z}) \to \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z}/N\mathbb{Z}))</m> for some <m>N \in \mathbb{N}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
      The group
      <me>
        \Gamma_0(N) = \{\begin{pmatrix}
          a \amp b \\
          c \amp d
        \end{pmatrix} \in \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z}) \mid c \equiv 0 \mod N\}
      </me>
      is a congruence subgroup. This is since the natural map 
      <m>
        \begin{align*}
        \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z}) \amp \to \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z}/N\mathbb{Z}) \\
        g \amp \mapsto g \mod N
        \end{align*}
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      has the kernel 
      <me>
        \{\begin{pmatrix}
          a \amp b \\
          c \amp d
        \end{pmatrix} \equiv  \begin{pmatrix}
          1 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 1
        \end{pmatrix} \mod N\}
      </me>
      which is clearly contained in <m>\Gamma_0(N)</m>.
    </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      Any character <m>\chi:(\mathbb{Z}/N\mathbb{Z})^{\times} \to \mathbb{C}^{\times}</m> extends to a congruence character
      <me>
        \chi_N: \Gamma_0(N) \to \mathbb{C}^{\times}, \:\: \chi(\begin{pmatrix}
        a \amp b \\
        c \amp d
      \end{pmatrix}) \to \chi(d)
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>M_k(\Gamma,\chi)</m> be the set of modular forms of weight <m>k</m>, character <m>\chi</m> for <m>\Gamma</m>. Then <m>M(k,\chi)</m> is a <m>\mathbb{C}</m>-vector space.
    </p>
    <remark>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>\begin{pmatrix}
                0 \amp -1 \\
                -1 \amp 0
                \end{pmatrix} = -I \in \Gamma
              </m>
              and <m>\chi(I) \neq (-1)^k</m>, then <m>M_k(\Gamma, \chi) = 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>f \in M_k(\Gamma, \chi), g \in \mathbb{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z}), f \mid_k g \in M_k(g\Gamma g, \chi_g)</m> where <m>\chi_g(\gamma) = \chi(g\gamma g^{-1})</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-cusp-forms">
    <title>Cusp forms</title>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>v_{\infty} = \text{inf}\{ n \in \mathbb{Q} \mid a_n(f) \neq 0\} \geq 0</m> and we say that <m>f</m> has a zero of order <m>v_{\infty}(f)</m> at <m>\infty</m>. We say that <m>f</m> has a zero at <m>\infty</m> if <m>v_{\infty}(f) > 0</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                A modular form <m>f</m> is a cusp form if <m>f \mid_k \gamma</m> has a zero at <m>\infty</m>, <m>\forall \gamma \in \Gamma \setminus \text{SL}_2(\mathbb{Z})</m>. We denote <m>S_k</m> be the set of cusp forms of weight <m>k</m>. We clearly have <m>S_k(\Gamma,\chi) \subset M_k(\Gamma,\chi)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <p>
        If <m>f</m> is a cusp form, then <m>f</m> is rapidly decreasing at <m>\infty</m> since
        <me>
          \lvert f \mid_{k} \gamma(z) \rvert = O(e^{-v_{\infty}(f \mid_k \gamma) 2\pi y})
        </me>
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      We present the following theorem without proof.
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>S_k(\Gamma,\chi)</m> and <m>M_k(\Gamma,\chi)</m> are finite-dimensional vector spaces over <m>\mathbb{C}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <remark>
      <p>
        We have <m>\oplus_{k,\chi} M_k(\Gamma,\chi) = M(\Gamma)</m> and <m>\oplus_{k,\chi} S_k(\Gamma,\chi) = S(\Gamma)</m> are an algebra.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      From above, the study of <m> M_k(\Gamma,\chi) </m> for congruence subgroup and congruence characters (<m>\text{Ker}(\chi)</m> congruence subgroup) can be reduced to the study of <m>M_k(\Gamma_0(N),\chi_N)</m> for some <m>N</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>




  

</section>